{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}
[[File:Claude Reignier Conder.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Claude Reignier Conder]]
'''Claude Reignier Conder''' (29 December 1848, [[Cheltenham]] – 16 February 1910, Cheltenham) was an English soldier, explorer and antiquarian.  He was a great-great-grandson of [[Louis-François Roubiliac]].<ref>{{cite book | title=Artists and their friends in England, 1700–1799, Volume 1 | author=William Thomas Whitley | publisher=The Medici society | year=1928 | page=93 }}</ref><ref name=pollock23>{{cite book | title=Kitchener: the road to Omdurman | author=John Charles Pollock | publisher=Constable | year=1998 | isbn=0-09-479140-6 | page=23}}</ref>

Conder was educated at [[University College London]] and the [[Royal Military Academy, Woolwich]].  He became a [[lieutenant]] in the [[Corps of Royal Engineers]] in 1870.  He carried out [[Survey of Western Palestine|survey work]] in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]] in 1872–1874, latterly in conjunction with Lt Kitchener, later [[Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener|Lord Kitchener]],<ref>{{cite book | title=Revealing the Holy Land: the photographic exploration of Palestine | first=Kathleen |last=Stewart Howe | publisher=University of California Press | year=1997 | isbn=0-89951-095-7 | pages=37–38}}</ref> whom he had met at school,<ref name=pollock23/><ref>British Empire. [http://www.britishempire.co.uk/forces/armycampaigns/africancampaigns/boerwar/kitchener.htm  Kitchener]</ref> and was seconded to the [[Palestine Exploration Fund]] from 1875 to 1878 and again in 1881 and 1882, when he was promoted captain.  He retired with the rank of colonel in 1904.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=CONDER, Claude Reignier|magazine=Who's Who|year=1907|volume= 59|page=371|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yEcuAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA371}}</ref>

Conder joined the [[1882 Anglo-Egyptian War|expedition to Egypt]] in 1882, under [[Garnet Wolseley, 1st Viscount Wolseley|Sir Garnet Wolseley]], to suppress the [[Urabi Revolt|rebellion]] of [[Ahmed ‘Urabi|Arabi Pasha]]. He was appointed a deputy assistant adjutant and quartermaster-general on the staff of the intelligence department. In Egypt his perfect knowledge of Arabic and of Eastern people proved most useful. He was present at the action of [[Kassassin]], the [[Battle of Tel el-Kebir]], and the advance to [[Cairo]], but then, seized with typhoid fever, he was invalided home. For his services he received the war medal with clasp for Tel el-Kebir, the [[Khedive]]'s bronze [[Khedive's Star|star]] and the fourth class of the [[Order of the Medjidie]].

While surveying the area of [[Safed]] in July 1875, Conder and his party were attacked by local residents, during which altercation Conder sustained a serious head injury which left him bed-ridden for a while and unable to return to Palestine.<ref>H.H. Kitchener, [http://biblicalstudies.org.uk/pdf/pefqs/1875_04_195.pdf An Account of the Safed Attack], ''Palestine Exploration Quarterly Statement'' 7.4 (Oct. 1875), pp. 195–199</ref> The work of surveying the country of Palestine commenced again only in late February 1877, without Conder.<ref>H.H. Kitchener, [http://biblicalstudies.org.uk/pdf/pefqs/1878-04_159.pdf Survey of Galilee],''Palestine Exploration Quarterly Statement'' (1878), pp. 159–174.</ref>  

Conder was first proposed as a  candidate for the [[Jack the Ripper]] murders by the author Tom Slemen.<ref>{{cite book | author=Tom Slemen | chapter=Towards a Solution | title=Jack the Ripper, British Intelligence Agent | year=2010 | publisher=Bluecoat Press | isbn=978-1-904438-91-5}}</ref>

