{{Infobox member of the Knesset | image= Gideon Ezra.jpg | birth_date = 30 June 1937 | birth_place = [[Jerusalem]], [[Mandatory Palestine]] | death_date = {{death date and age|2012|5|17|1937|6|30|df=y}} | Knesset(s) = [[Israeli legislative election, 1996|14]], [[Israeli legislative election, 1999|15]], [[Israeli legislative election, 2003|16]], [[Israeli legislative election, 2006|17]], [[Israeli legislative election, 2009|18]] | party1 = [[Likud]] | partyyears1 = 1996–2005 | party2 = [[Kadima]] | partyyears2 = 2005–2012 | minister1 = {{nowrap|[[Minister in the Prime Minister's Office]]}} | ministeryears1 = 2003–2004 | minister2 = [[Tourism Minister of Israel|Minister of Tourism]] | ministeryears2 = 2004–2005 | minister3 = [[Internal Security Minister of Israel|Minister of Internal Security]] | ministeryears3 = 2004–2006 | minister4 = [[Environmental Protection Minister of Israel|Minister of Environmental Protection]] | ministeryears4 = 2006–2009 }}
'''Gideon Ezra''' ({{lang-he|גדעון עזרא}}, 30 June 1937 – 17 May 2012) was an [[Israel]]i politician. He served as a member of the [[Knesset]] for [[Likud]] and [[Kadima]] between 1996 and 2012, and also held several ministerial portfolios.
==Biography== Ezra's family came originally as immigrants from [[Iraq]] and settled in [[Mandatory Palestine|Palestine]]. He was born in [[Jerusalem]] and served in the [[Israeli Defense Force]] between 1955 and 1958 in the [[Nahal]]. He studied geography and political science at the [[University of Haifa]]. He worked for the [[Shin Bet]] from 1962 to 1995. After leaving the service, he served as an advisor to then Minister of Internal Security, [[Moshe Shahal]].
===Political career=== Ezra was elected to the Knesset in the [[Israeli legislative election, 1996|1996 elections]] on the [[Likud]] list, and retained his seat in the [[Israeli legislative election, 1999|1999]] and [[Israeli legislative election, 2003|2003 elections]]. After [[Ariel Sharon]] beat [[Ehud Barak]] in the [[Israeli prime ministerial election, 2001|2001 election for Prime Minister]], Ezra was appointed Deputy Minister of Internal Security. He was given his first full ministerial position after the 2003 elections when appointed Minister in the Ministry of the Prime Minister's Office. When [[Binyamin Elon]] was sacked as [[Tourism Minister of Israel|Minister of Tourism]] in July 2004, Ezra replaced him, initially as Acting Minister (the position was made permanent at the end of August). From September 2004 he also held the position of Acting [[Internal Security Minister of Israel|Minister of Internal Security]] after [[Tzachi Hanegbi]] resigned in the face of corruption allegations. This ministerial post was also made permanent in November, and Ezra oversaw the evacuation of the [[Amona, Mateh Binyamin|Amona]] settlement in February 2006. In November 2005 he was attacked during a rally in [[Sderot]] against [[Israel's unilateral disengagement plan]] over his support for it.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120708212002/http://fr.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1130954356981&pagename=JPost/JPArticle/ShowFull "Anything is possible"], ''Jerusalem Post'', 8 November 2005</ref>
In January 2005 he was replaced as Tourism Minister by [[Avraham Hirschson]]. When Sharon founded [[Kadima]] in late 2005, Ezra joined him, picking up the Environment Ministry portfolio from Labor's [[Shalom Simhon]]. After the [[Israeli legislative election, 2006|2006 elections]] he was appointed Minister of Environmental Protection by [[Ehud Olmert]]. In April 2007 he opposed plans to build a solar energy plant near [[Dimona]] to avoid harm to a nature reserve.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/850922.html "Environment chief: New clean energy site would harm rare species"], Haaretz, 20 April 2007</ref> He has also overseen the expansion of [[container deposit legislation]] to cover 1.5 litre bottles.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/821690.html Government expands deposit law to include 1.5 liter bottles] Haaretz, 4 February 2007</ref>
He retained his seat again in the [[Israeli legislative election, 2009|2009 elections]], having been placed twelfth on the Kadima list. However, he lost his place in the cabinet as the Likud-led coalition formed the government. On 17 May 2012, aged 74, Ezra died of lung cancer after a two-year battle with the disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4230417,00.html|title=MK Gideon Ezra dies at 74, ''Israel News''|publisher=Ynetnews.com|date=20 June 1995|accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> He was succeeded by [[Akram Hasson]].
